Appendix A: Foundations of Differential Geometry

A.1 Riemannian Manifolds

Let M be a smooth manifold of dimension n. A Riemannian metric g assigns to each point p \in M an inner product g_p: T_pM \times T_pM \to \mathbb{R} that varies smoothly. In local coordinates (x^1,\dots,x^n), we write

g = g_{ij}(x) \, dx^i \otimes dx^j,

where (g_{ij}) is a symmetric positive-definite matrix and the Einstein summation convention is used.

Definition A.1 (Levi-Civita connection). The unique torsion-free connection \nabla compatible with g (i.e., \nabla g = 0) is given in coordinates by

\nabla_{\partial_i} \partial_j = \Gamma^k_{ij} \partial_k,

with Christoffel symbols

\Gamma^k_{ij} = \frac{1}{2} g^{k\ell} (\partial_i g_{j\ell} + \partial_j g_{i\ell} - \partial_\ell g_{ij}).

Definition A.2 (Riemann curvature tensor). The curvature of \nabla is defined by

R(X,Y)Z = \nabla_X \nabla_Y Z - \nabla_Y \nabla_X Z - \nabla_{[X,Y]} Z.

In components,

R(\partial_i,\partial_j)\partial_k = R_{ijk}^{\;\;\;\; \ell} \partial_\ell,

where

R_{ijk}^{\;\;\;\; \ell} = \partial_i \Gamma^\ell_{jk} - \partial_j \Gamma^\ell_{ik} + \Gamma^m_{jk} \Gamma^\ell_{im} - \Gamma^m_{ik} \Gamma^\ell_{jm}.

Definition A.3 (Ricci curvature). The Ricci tensor is the trace of the curvature:

\operatorname{Ric}_{ij} = R_{ikj}^{\;\;\;\; k} = g^{k\ell} R_{ikj\ell}.

For a unit vector v \in T_pM, \operatorname{Ric}(v,v) measures the average sectional curvature of planes containing v.

Definition A.4 (Geodesics and exponential map). A curve \gamma: [0,1] \to M is a geodesic if \nabla_{\dot\gamma}\dot\gamma = 0. The exponential map \exp_p: T_pM \to M sends v to \gamma_v(1), where \gamma_v is the unique geodesic with \gamma_v(0)=p and \dot\gamma_v(0)=v.

A.2 Gradient Flows on Manifolds

Definition A.5 (Gradient). For a smooth function f: M \to \mathbb{R}, the gradient \operatorname{grad}_g f is the unique vector field satisfying

g(\operatorname{grad}_g f, X) = df(X) \quad \forall X \in \mathfrak{X}(M).

In coordinates,

(\operatorname{grad}_g f)^i = g^{ij} \partial_j f.

Definition A.6 (Gradient flow). The gradient flow of f is the curve \theta(t) satisfying

\dot{\theta}(t) = -\operatorname{grad}_g f(\theta(t)).

Lemma A.7 (Energy dissipation). Along a gradient flow,

\frac{d}{dt} f(\theta(t)) = -\|\operatorname{grad}_g f(\theta(t))\|^2_g \le 0.

A.3 Geodesic Convexity

Definition A.8 (Geodesic convexity). A function f: M \to \mathbb{R} is geodesically convex if for every geodesic \gamma:[0,1]\to M,

f(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t) f(\gamma(0)) + t f(\gamma(1)).

It is \mu-strongly geodesically convex if

f(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t) f(\gamma(0)) + t f(\gamma(1)) - \frac{\mu}{2} t(1-t) d(\gamma(0),\gamma(1))^2.

Proposition A.9 (Characterization via Hessian). A function f is \mu-strongly geodesically convex iff \nabla^2 f \succeq \mu g as quadratic forms, where \nabla^2 f is the Hessian with respect to the Levi-Civita connection:

(\nabla^2 f)(X,Y) = X(Yf) - (\nabla_X Y)f.

Theorem A.10 (Polyak–Łojasiewicz inequality). For a \mu-strongly geodesically convex function f with unique minimizer x^*,

\|\operatorname{grad}_g f(x)\|^2_g \ge 2\mu (f(x) - f(x^*)) \quad \forall x \in M.

A.4 Bakry–Émery Theory

Definition A.11 (Curvature-dimension condition). For a diffusion generator \mathcal{L} = \Delta_g - \nabla V \cdot \nabla with invariant measure \pi \propto e^{-V}, we define the carré du champ operator

\Gamma(f) = \frac{1}{2} \mathcal{L}(f^2) - f\mathcal{L}f = \|\nabla f\|^2_g.

The iterated operator is

\Gamma_2(f) = \frac{1}{2} \mathcal{L}\Gamma(f) - \Gamma(f, \mathcal{L}f).

Theorem A.12 (Bakry–Émery criterion). For the Langevin generator,

\Gamma_2(f) = \|\nabla^2 f\|^2_{\text{HS}} + (\operatorname{Ric}_g + \nabla^2 V)(\nabla f, \nabla f).

If \operatorname{Ric}_g + \nabla^2 V \ge \rho g, then the generator satisfies the curvature-dimension condition CD(\rho, \infty).

Corollary A.13 (Log-Sobolev inequality). Under CD(\rho, \infty) with \rho > 0, the invariant measure \pi satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant \rho:

\operatorname{Ent}_\pi(f^2) \le \frac{2}{\rho} \int \|\nabla f\|^2_g \, d\pi.

