Appendix B: Information Geometry

B.1 Statistical Manifolds

Definition B.1 (Statistical model). A parametric family of probability distributions \{p_\theta : \theta \in \Theta\} with \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n open is a statistical model if the map \theta \mapsto p_\theta is injective and sufficiently smooth.

Definition B.2 (Fisher information metric). Under regularity conditions, the Fisher information matrix is

g_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\!\left[ \partial_i \ell_\theta \, \partial_j \ell_\theta \right] = \int p_\theta(x) \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^j} dx,

where \ell_\theta(x) = \log p_\theta(x). This defines a Riemannian metric on \Theta.

B.2 Exponential Families

Definition B.3 (Exponential family). A statistical model of the form

p_\theta(x) = \exp\!\big( \theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta) \big) h(x)

is an exponential family, where \theta \in \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n are natural parameters, T(x) are sufficient statistics, and \psi(\theta) is the log-partition function.

Proposition B.4 (Fisher metric for exponential families). For an exponential family,

g_{ij}(\theta) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta).

Proof. Differentiating \log p_\theta = \theta \cdot T - \psi + \log h gives \partial_i \log p_\theta = T_i - \partial_i \psi. Then

g_{ij} = \mathbb{E}_\theta[(T_i - \partial_i \psi)(T_j - \partial_j \psi)] = \operatorname{Cov}_\theta(T_i, T_j) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi.

The last equality follows from the fact that \partial_i \psi = \mathbb{E}_\theta[T_i] and \partial_i \partial_j \psi = \operatorname{Cov}_\theta(T_i, T_j). ∎

B.3 Dual Connections and Dually Flat Spaces

Definition B.5 (Dual connections). Two affine connections \nabla and \nabla^* on a Riemannian manifold (M,g) are dual if

X g(Y,Z) = g(\nabla_X Y, Z) + g(Y, \nabla^*_X Z) \quad \forall X,Y,Z \in \mathfrak{X}(M).

Definition B.6 (Dually flat space). A statistical manifold (M,g,\nabla,\nabla^*) is dually flat if both \nabla and \nabla^* are flat (zero curvature) and dual with respect to g.

Theorem B.7 (Dual coordinate systems). In a dually flat space, there exist affine coordinate systems \theta^i (∇-affine) and \eta_i (∇*-affine) such that

g(\partial_i, \partial^j) = \delta_i^j,

where \partial_i = \partial/\partial\theta^i and \partial^j = \partial/\partial\eta_j.

Definition B.8 (Potentials). There exist functions \psi(\theta) and \varphi(\eta), Legendre duals, satisfying

\eta_i = \partial_i \psi(\theta), \quad \theta^i = \partial^i \varphi(\eta), \quad \psi(\theta) + \varphi(\eta) = \theta^i \eta_i.

Definition B.9 (Canonical divergence). The canonical divergence of a dually flat space is

D(\theta \parallel \theta') = \psi(\theta') + \varphi(\eta) - \theta^i \eta_i',

where \eta = \nabla\psi(\theta). This is equivalent to the Kullback-Leibler divergence for exponential families.

B.4 Gradient and Hessian of Entropy

Proposition B.10 (Gradient of entropy for exponential families). For an exponential family in natural parameters,

\operatorname{grad}_g H = -\theta,

where H(\theta) = -\mathbb{E}_\theta[\log p_\theta(X)] is the Shannon entropy.

Proof. First compute partial derivatives:

H(\theta) = \psi(\theta) - \theta \cdot \eta(\theta) - \mathbb{E}_\theta[\log h(X)].

Differentiating with respect to \theta^j:

\partial_j H = \partial_j \psi - \eta_j - \theta^k \partial_j \eta_k.

But \partial_j \psi = \eta_j and \partial_j \eta_k = \partial_j \partial_k \psi = g_{jk}. Thus

\partial_j H = -\theta^k g_{jk}.

Now compute the gradient:

(\operatorname{grad}_g H)^i = g^{ij} \partial_j H = -g^{ij} \theta^k g_{jk} = -\theta^k \delta^i_k = -\theta^i.

Hence \operatorname{grad}_g H = -\theta. ∎

Proposition B.11 (Hessian of entropy). The Hessian of -H with respect to the Levi-Civita connection satisfies

\nabla^2_g (-H) = g.

Proof. In expectation parameters \eta, the metric becomes Euclidean (g_{ij} = \delta_{ij}) and -H is a quadratic function: -H(\eta) = \frac{1}{2}\|\eta\|^2 + \text{constant}. The Hessian in these coordinates is simply the identity matrix. Since the Levi-Civita connection in Euclidean coordinates has vanishing Christoffel symbols, the result follows. ∎

B.5 Categorical Fisher Information

Definition B.12 (Categorical Fisher information). For a classification task with categories y \in \mathcal{Y} and model p(y|x,\theta), the categorical Fisher information is

J_{\text{cat}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log p(y|x,\theta) \nabla_\theta \log p(y|x,\theta)^\top \right].

Theorem B.13 (Bonnasse-Gahot & Nadal, 2025). Minimizing the Bayes risk (cross-entropy loss) implies maximizing the mutual information between categories and neural representations. At the optimum, the neural Fisher information aligns with the categorical Fisher information:

g_{\text{neural}}(\theta) \approx J_{\text{cat}}(\theta)

up to scaling and within the relevant subspace. This alignment induces expansion of neural space near decision boundaries—a phenomenon known as categorical perception.

B.6 Cencov's Theorem

Theorem B.14 (Cencov, 1982). The Fisher metric is the unique Riemannian metric (up to scaling) on the simplex of probability distributions that is invariant under congruent embeddings by Markov morphisms.

Corollary B.15 (Markov kernels are contractions). For any Markov kernel k: M \to N between statistical manifolds equipped with Fisher metrics,

k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M,

i.e., the pullback metric is pointwise less than or equal to the original metric. In particular, for any tangent vector v \in T_pM,

g_N( (dk)_p v, (dk)_p v) \le g_M(v, v).

