Appendix C: Category Theory Details

C.1 Categories, Functors, and Natural Transformations

Definition C.1 (Category). A category \mathbf{C} consists of:

· A collection of objects \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{C})
· For each pair A,B \in \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{C}), a set \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,B) of morphisms
· For each A \in \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{C}), an identity morphism \operatorname{id}_A \in \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,A)
· A composition operation \circ: \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(B,C) \times \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,B) \to \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,C)

satisfying:

· Associativity: (h \circ g) \circ f = h \circ (g \circ f) whenever defined
· Identity: f \circ \operatorname{id}_A = f = \operatorname{id}_B \circ f for f: A \to B

Definition C.2 (Functor). A functor F: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{D} consists of:

· A mapping on objects: F(A) \in \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{D}) for each A \in \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{C})
· A mapping on morphisms: F(f): F(A) \to F(B) for each f: A \to B in \mathbf{C}

satisfying:

· F(\operatorname{id}_A) = \operatorname{id}_{F(A)}
· F(g \circ f) = F(g) \circ F(f)

Definition C.3 (Natural transformation). For functors F,G: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{D}, a natural transformation \alpha: F \Rightarrow G is a family of morphisms \alpha_A: F(A) \to G(A) in \mathbf{D}, one for each A \in \operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{C}), such that for every morphism f: A \to B in \mathbf{C}, the following diagram commutes:

\begin{CD}
F(A) @>{\alpha_A}>> G(A) \\
@V{F(f)}VV @VV{G(f)}V \\
F(B) @>>{\alpha_B}> G(B)
\end{CD}

C.2 Monads and Kleisli Categories

Definition C.4 (Monad). A monad on a category \mathbf{C} is a triple (T, \eta, \mu) where:

· T: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{C} is an endofunctor
· \eta: \operatorname{Id}_{\mathbf{C}} \Rightarrow T is a natural transformation (the unit)
· \mu: T^2 \Rightarrow T is a natural transformation (the multiplication)

satisfying the following coherence laws for all objects A:

1. \mu_A \circ T(\eta_A) = \operatorname{id}_{T(A)}
2. \mu_A \circ \eta_{T(A)} = \operatorname{id}_{T(A)}
3. \mu_A \circ T(\mu_A) = \mu_A \circ \mu_{T(A)}

Definition C.5 (Kleisli category). Given a monad (T, \eta, \mu) on \mathbf{C}, the Kleisli category \mathbf{C}_T has:

· Objects: the same objects as \mathbf{C}
· Morphisms: a Kleisli morphism f: A \to B is a morphism f: A \to T(B) in \mathbf{C}
· Composition: for f: A \to B and g: B \to C, the Kleisli composition is
  g \circ_T f = \mu_C \circ T(g) \circ f
· Identity: \eta_A: A \to T(A) is the identity in \mathbf{C}_T

C.3 The Category Stat

Definition C.6 (Objects of Stat). An object of \mathbf{Stat} is a statistical manifold (M, g, (\nabla, \nabla^*)), where M is a smooth manifold of probability distributions, g is the Fisher-Rao metric, and (\nabla, \nabla^*) are dual torsion-free connections making M dually flat.

Definition C.7 (Morphisms of Stat). A morphism k: M \to N is a Markov kernel k: M \times \Sigma_N \to [0,1] such that the induced push-forward map k_*: \mathcal{P}(M) \to \mathcal{P}(N) satisfies the information contraction property:

k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M,

i.e., for all tangent vectors v \in T_mM,

g_N( (dk)_m v, (dk)_m v) \le g_M(v, v).

Proposition C.8 (Composition in Stat). If k: M \to N and \ell: N \to P are morphisms in \mathbf{Stat}, then \ell \circ k defined by

(\ell \circ k)(p)(A) = \int_N \ell(q)(A) \, k(p)(dq)

is also a morphism.

Proof. By the data processing inequality (Corollary B.15), Markov kernels are Fisher contractions. The composition of contractions remains a contraction. ∎

Definition C.9 (Identity in Stat). The identity morphism \operatorname{id}_M: M \to M is the Dirac kernel: \operatorname{id}_M(p) = \delta_p.

C.4 The Intentional Monad

Let (\mathcal{G}, *, e) be a Lie monoid equipped with a bi-invariant Fisher metric (so left and right translations are isometries). This represents the space of possible goals.

Definition C.10 (Goal-augmented manifold). For an object M in \mathbf{Stat}, define T_0(M) = M \times \mathcal{G} with the product Fisher metric g_{M\times\mathcal{G}} = g_M \oplus g_{\mathcal{G}} and the product dual connections.

Definition C.11 (Intentional monad). Define the intentional monad T on \mathbf{Stat} as:

· Endofunctor: T(M) = M \times \mathcal{G}. For a morphism k: M \to N, define T(k): T(M) \to T(N) by T(k)(m, g) = (k(m), g).
· Unit: \eta_M: M \to T(M) is the embedding \eta_M(m) = (m, e).
· Multiplication: \mu_M: T(T(M)) = (M \times \mathcal{G}) \times \mathcal{G} \to M \times \mathcal{G} by \mu_M((m, g_1), g_2) = (m, g_1 * g_2).

Proposition C.12 (Monad laws). The triple (T, \eta, \mu) satisfies the monad laws.

Proof.

1. \mu_M \circ T(\eta_M)(m, g) = \mu_M((\eta_M(m), g)) = \mu_M(((m, e), g)) = (m, e * g) = (m, g).
2. \mu_M \circ \eta_{T(M)}(m, g) = \mu_M(((m, g), e)) = (m, g * e) = (m, g).
3. \mu_M \circ T(\mu_M)((m, g_1), g_2, g_3) = \mu_M((m, g_1 * g_2), g_3) = (m, (g_1 * g_2) * g_3) and
   \mu_M \circ \mu_{T(M)}((m, g_1), g_2, g_3) = \mu_M((m, g_1), g_2 * g_3) = (m, g_1 * (g_2 * g_3)). These are equal by associativity of *. ∎

C.5 Kleisli Morphisms and Intentionality

Definition C.13 (Intentional morphism). A Kleisli morphism f: M \to N in \mathbf{Stat}_T is a morphism f: M \to T(N) in \mathbf{Stat}. For endomorphisms (M = N), we call f \epsilon-intentional if for every m \in M,

d_M(m, \pi_M \circ f(m)) \le \epsilon,

where \pi_M: T(M) \to M is the projection onto the first factor.

Proposition C.14 (Composition of intentional morphisms). If f, g: M \to T(M) are \epsilon_f and \epsilon_g-intentional endomorphisms, then g \circ_T f is (\epsilon_f + \epsilon_g)-intentional.

Proof. For any m \in M, write f(m) = (b, g_f) with b = \pi_M(f(m)). Then

(g \circ_T f)(m) = \mu_M(T(g)(b, g_f)) = \mu_M((g(b), g_f)) = (c, g_g * g_f),

where g(b) = (c, g_g). Thus \pi_M((g \circ_T f)(m)) = c. By the triangle inequality,

d_M(m, c) \le d_M(m, b) + d_M(b, c) \le \epsilon_f + \epsilon_g. \quad \blacksquare

