Appendix F: Diagonal-Plus-Low-Rank (DPLR) Analysis for Kimi Delta Attention

F.1 Kimi Delta Attention Update Rule

Following Kimi Team (2025), the Kimi Delta Attention (KDA) update is given by:

S_t = \Lambda_t S_{t-1} + U_t V_t^\top,

where:

· S_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times d_v} is the state matrix at time t
· \Lambda_t = \operatorname{Diag}(\alpha_t) \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times d_k} is a diagonal matrix of channel-wise decay factors
· U_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k \times r}, V_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_v \times r} are low-rank matrices with rank r \ll d_k, d_v

F.2 Metric Evolution

Proposition F.1 (Metric update). Let g_t be the Fisher information metric of the state S_t (viewed as a vector in \mathbb{R}^{d_k d_v}). Under the KDA update,

g_{t} = (\Lambda_t \otimes I_{d_v}) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I_{d_v})^\top + \Delta_t,

where \Delta_t \succeq 0 is the contribution from the low-rank term, and \otimes denotes the Kronecker product.

Proof. Vectorizing the state, let s_t = \operatorname{vec}(S_t) \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k d_v}. The update becomes

s_t = (\Lambda_t \otimes I_{d_v}) s_{t-1} + \operatorname{vec}(U_t V_t^\top).

The Fisher information transforms according to the Jacobian of this transformation. The Jacobian with respect to s_{t-1} is \Lambda_t \otimes I_{d_v}. The low-rank term adds a positive semidefinite contribution to the metric. ∎

F.3 Eigenvalue Bounds

Theorem F.2 (DPLR eigenvalue bounds). Under the assumptions that U_t, V_t are Fisher-contracting (as linear maps), the eigenvalues of the Fisher information metric g_t satisfy:

\lambda_{\min}(g_t) \ge \lambda_{\min}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \min(1, \alpha_s^2),

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \max(1, \alpha_s^2).

Proof. We prove the upper bound; the lower bound is similar.

For any unit vector x \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k d_v},

x^\top g_t x = x^\top (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x + x^\top \Delta_t x.

Since \Delta_t \succeq 0, the second term is non-negative, so

x^\top g_t x \le x^\top (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x + \text{positive}.

The maximum eigenvalue satisfies:

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) = \max_{\|x\|=1} x^\top g_t x.

For any x, let y = (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x. Then

\|y\| \le \|\Lambda_t \otimes I\| \|x\| = \|\Lambda_t\| = \max_i |\alpha_t^i|.

Thus

x^\top (\Lambda_t \otimes I) g_{t-1} (\Lambda_t \otimes I)^\top x \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \|y\|^2 \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \max_i |\alpha_t^i|^2.

Taking the maximum over x on both sides,

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_{t-1}) \max_i \alpha_{t,i}^2.

Iterating this inequality from t down to 1 yields:

\lambda_{\max}(g_t) \le \lambda_{\max}(g_0) \prod_{s=1}^t \max_i \alpha_{s,i}^2.

The lower bound follows by considering the inverse metric and using the fact that low-rank updates cannot decrease the minimum eigenvalue beyond the diagonal scaling. Specifically,

g_t^{-1} \preceq (\Lambda_t^{-1} \otimes I) g_{t-1}^{-1} (\Lambda_t^{-1} \otimes I)^\top,

and applying the same argument yields the bound on \lambda_{\min}(g_t) = 1/\lambda_{\max}(g_t^{-1}). ∎

F.4 Implications for Stability

Corollary F.3 (Stability over long contexts). If \alpha_t^i \in [\alpha_{\min}, \alpha_{\max}] with 0 < \alpha_{\min} \le 1 \le \alpha_{\max} < \infty, then the condition number \kappa(g_t) = \lambda_{\max}(g_t)/\lambda_{\min}(g_t) satisfies:

\kappa(g_t) \le \kappa(g_0) \left( \frac{\alpha_{\max}}{\alpha_{\min}} \right)^{2t}.

For typical KDA implementations, \alpha_t \approx 1 (near-perfect memory for important features) and \alpha_{\min} \approx \alpha_{\max}, so the condition number remains bounded even as t \to \infty. This explains the empirical observation of stable training over 1M token contexts (Kimi Team, 2025).

