Appendix G: Stochastic Intentional Flows

G.1 Langevin Dynamics on Manifolds

Definition G.1 (Langevin SDE). On a Riemannian manifold (M, g), the Langevin SDE for a potential \mathcal{L}_\lambda is:

d\theta_t = -\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta_t) \, dt + \sqrt{2\beta^{-1}} \, dW_t,

where dW_t is the Brownian motion on M (generated by the Laplace-Beltrami operator \Delta_g).

Definition G.2 (Generator). The infinitesimal generator of this diffusion is:

\mathcal{L} = \Delta_g - \operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_\lambda \cdot \nabla = e^{\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda} \operatorname{div}_g \left( e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda} \nabla \right).

Proposition G.3 (Invariant measure). The unique invariant measure of the Langevin diffusion is the Gibbs measure:

\pi(d\theta) = \frac{1}{Z} e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta)} \operatorname{vol}_g(d\theta),

where Z = \int_M e^{-\beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda} \operatorname{vol}_g is the partition function.

G.2 Bakry-Émery Theory for Langevin Dynamics

Theorem G.4 (Bakry-Émery criterion for Langevin). For the Langevin generator with potential V = \beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda, the curvature-dimension condition CD(\rho, \infty) holds with

\rho = \inf_{\theta \in M} \lambda_{\min}\left( \operatorname{Ric}_g(\theta) + \nabla^2 V(\theta) \right).

Proof. From Theorem A.12, \Gamma_2(f) = \|\nabla^2 f\|^2_{\text{HS}} + (\operatorname{Ric}_g + \nabla^2 V)(\nabla f, \nabla f). The smallest eigenvalue of \operatorname{Ric}_g + \nabla^2 V gives the optimal \rho. ∎

G.3 Convergence to Equilibrium

Theorem G.5 (Exponential convergence). Assume \operatorname{Ric}_g \ge \rho g and \mathcal{L}_\lambda is \mu-strongly convex. Then for the Langevin diffusion with potential V = \beta \mathcal{L}_\lambda, we have \rho_{\text{total}} = \rho + \beta\mu. Consequently:

1. The generator satisfies CD(\rho_{\text{total}}, \infty).
2. The invariant measure \pi satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant \rho_{\text{total}}.
3. For any function f with \int f d\pi = 0,
   \|P_t f\|_{L^2(\pi)} \le e^{-\rho_{\text{total}} t} \|f\|_{L^2(\pi)}.
4. In particular, the law of \theta_t converges exponentially to \pi in relative entropy:
   \operatorname{Ent}_\pi(P_t f) \le e^{-2\rho_{\text{total}} t} \operatorname{Ent}_\pi(f).

Proof. From Theorem G.4, \rho_{\text{total}} = \inf_{\theta} \lambda_{\min}(\operatorname{Ric}_g + \beta \nabla^2 \mathcal{L}_\lambda) \ge \rho + \beta\mu. The log-Sobolev inequality follows from the Bakry-Émery theorem (Theorem A.13). Exponential convergence in L^2 and entropy are standard consequences of the log-Sobolev inequality (Bakry et al., 2014). ∎

Corollary G.6 (Convergence in \chi^2 divergence). Under the same conditions,

\chi^2(P_t f \parallel \pi) \le e^{-2\rho_{\text{total}} t} \chi^2(f \parallel \pi).

