Appendix I: Additional Lemmas

I.1 Lemma: Gradient Flow of Strongly Convex Function Converges Exponentially

Lemma I.1. Let f be a \mu-strongly geodesically convex function on a complete Riemannian manifold M with unique minimizer x^*. Then for any solution of \dot{x} = -\nabla f(x),

f(x(t)) - f(x^*) \le e^{-2\mu t} \big( f(x(0)) - f(x^*) \big).

Proof. See Theorem D.1. ∎

I.2 Lemma: Composition of Contractions is a Contraction

Lemma I.2. If k: M \to N and \ell: N \to P are morphisms in \mathbf{Stat}, then \ell \circ k is also a morphism.

Proof. For any p,q \in \mathcal{P}(M), the data processing inequality gives

D_{KL}\big( (\ell \circ k)_* p \parallel (\ell \circ k)_* q \big) \le D_{KL}(k_* p \parallel k_* q) \le D_{KL}(p \parallel q).

Since the Fisher metric is generated by the KL divergence, this implies the contraction property on tangent vectors. ∎

I.3 Lemma: Lipschitz Bound for Attention Mechanism

Lemma I.3. Consider an attention head with parameters Q,K,V and softmax activation. The map \operatorname{Attn}: M^n \to M^n defined by

\operatorname{Attn}(\theta_1,\dots,\theta_n)_i = \sum_{j=1}^n \alpha_{ij}(\theta) \theta_j,

with \alpha_{ij}(\theta) = \frac{\exp( \langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_j \rangle / \sqrt{d} )}{\sum_k \exp( \langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_k \rangle / \sqrt{d} )}, is a morphism in \mathbf{Stat} (i.e., it satisfies the information contraction property) with Lipschitz constant L \le 1 with respect to the product Fisher metric.

Proof. The map \operatorname{Attn} is a convex combination of the input distributions, hence a Markov kernel in each coordinate. By Cencov's theorem (Theorem B.14), any Markov kernel is a contraction of the Fisher metric. The product metric on M^n is the sum of the individual metrics, so the contraction property holds componentwise, implying \operatorname{Attn} is a morphism. The Lipschitz bound follows from the fact that the operator norm of a stochastic matrix is 1. ∎

I.4 Lemma: Bregman Divergence is Convex

Lemma I.4. The Bregman divergence D_{\text{BR}}(g \parallel J) = \frac{1}{2}(\operatorname{tr}(g^{-1}J) - \log \det(g^{-1}J) - n) is strictly convex in g on the space of positive definite matrices.

Proof. The function f(g) = -\log \det g is strictly convex, and \operatorname{tr}(g^{-1}J) is convex in g (it is the perspective of a quadratic form). The sum of a strictly convex and a convex function is strictly convex. ∎

